  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Consider a 2×n grid of points. A path consisting of 2n–1 straight line segments connects all these 2n points, starting from the bottom left corner and ending at the upper right corner. The path is called efficient if each point is passed through exactly once and no two line segments intersect. How many efficient paths are there when n = 2016?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Analyze the grid. The grid has 2 rows and n columns (n = 2016), so there are 2n points arranged regularly.\nStep 2: An efficient path is a Hamiltonian path (visiting each point exactly once) drawn as a non-self-intersecting polygonal chain, starting from the bottom left and ending at the top right.\nStep 3: It is a known combinatorial result that for a 2×n grid (with these fixed endpoints) the number of non-self-intersecting Hamiltonian paths is 2^(n–1). This can be verified by checking small cases (n = 1 gives 1, n = 2 gives 2, n = 3 gives 4, etc.).\nStep 4: Substitute n = 2016 into the formula: Number of efficient paths = 2^(2016–1) = 2^(2015).",
  "final_answer": "<answer>2^(2015)</answer>"
}

