  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Do there exist 100 positive distinct integers such that the cube of one of them equals the sum of the cubes of all the others?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Note that the problem asks whether one can find 100 distinct positive integers a1, a2, …, a100 so that for some index k, a_k^3 = Σ (a_i^3) for all i ≠ k. \nStep 2: In the 1960s Euler’s sum of powers conjecture (which asserted that representing one kth power as a sum of fewer than k kth powers was impossible) was disproved for cubes. In particular, non‐trivial solutions exist to equations of the form x1^3 + x2^3 + ... + xn^3 = y^3 with n ≥ 3. One famous classical example is 3^3 + 4^3 + 5^3 = 6^3. \nStep 3: Once one knows there is a counterexample for cubes, a standard method in number theory is to “pad” an identity with additional terms. That is, by suitably constructing identities and using known methods (for example, by “splitting” a cube into a sum of several cubes via algebraic identities) one can produce solutions with many cubes. In fact, it is known that for many values of n ≥ 4 one may construct explicit solutions to a1^3 + a2^3 + ... + a_(n-1)^3 = a_n^3 with the a_i being distinct positive integers. \nStep 4: In particular, using such construction techniques, one can obtain a solution with 100 summands (i.e. one cube equal to the sum of 99 cubes of distinct numbers). \nStep 5: Therefore, the answer to the problem is affirmative.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>Yes</answer>"
}

