  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Given an alphabet of 16 letters, every word in a language has exactly 3 letters. The language is defined so that no word's first letter is the same as any word's last letter. Determine the maximum possible number of words in the language.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Let each word be of the form (first letter, middle letter, last letter). The condition implies that if we collect all first letters used across words (set F) and all last letters used (set L), then F and L must be disjoint. 2. The middle letter can be any of the 16 letters. 3. To maximize the number of words, we maximize the number of choices for the first and last letters subject to F ∩ L = ∅. Let |F| = a and |L| = b, with a + b ≤ 16. 4. For a fixed partition with a elements chosen as possible first letters and b elements as possible last letters, the number of possible words is a * 16 * b = 16ab. 5. With the constraint a + b = 16 (using all letters) and a, b are nonnegative integers, the product ab is maximized when a and b are as equal as possible. The maximum occurs when a = 8 and b = 8. 6. Therefore, the maximum number of words is 16 * 8 * 8 = 16 * 64 = 1024.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>1024</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>\"574 board\" (the number 574 appears with no clear meaning) and \"Did you hear that the new coffee shop downtown is offering a buy-one-get-one-free deal on their summer flavors?\"</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let n be an even positive integer. On an n × n board, two different cells are said to be neighboring if they share a common side. Find the minimal number of cells that must be marked so that every cell (whether marked or not) has at least one marked neighboring cell.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. The problem asks for a total dominating set of the grid, i.e. a set of marked cells such that every cell in the grid has a marked neighbor (note that a cell does not count as its own neighbor). \n2. A common technique for problems on grid graphs is to use a partition (or coloring) of the board. However, simply marking one color in a chessboard coloring does not work because any marked cell would have all neighbors in the opposite (and unmarked) color and therefore would not be dominated. \n3. For an even n, it is known that one can partition the board into 2 × 2 blocks. In each 2 × 2 block one can choose a pairing of adjacent cells such that both marked cells serve as neighbors to each other and also help dominate cells in adjacent blocks. \n4. An optimal pattern that achieves the total domination property uses exactly half of the cells of the board. More rigorous analyses in grid total domination show that for an even × even grid the minimum number is n²/2. \n5. Verification: For n = 2, the board has 4 cells and a total of 2 marked cells arranged as adjacent cells suffice, which is 2 = 2²/2. The general pattern extends to larger even n.\n6. Thus, the minimal number of marked cells required is n²/2.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>n²/2</answer>"
}

