  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Determine the greatest positive integer n such that in three-dimensional space there exist n points P₁, P₂, …, Pₙ, no three of which are collinear, and for any distinct indices i, j, k the triangle PᵢPⱼPₖ is not obtuse.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Recognize that the condition requires every triangle determined by any three chosen points to have no angle greater than 90°. Such sets are known in the literature as nonobtuse sets (allowing right angles). A known result in Euclidean geometry states that in d-dimensional space, any set of points with this property has at most 2ᵈ points. Here d = 3, so the upper bound is 2³ = 8.\nStep 2: To show the bound is sharp, one may construct an example. The vertices of a cube (or any parallelotope with appropriately scaled edges) provide 8 points in ℝ³. One can verify that for any three vertices of a cube the resulting triangle is nonobtuse (all angles are at most 90°).\nStep 3: Therefore, the greatest possible n is 8.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>8</answer>"
}

