  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>For what value of k is the line through the points (3, 2k+1) and (8, 4k-5) parallel to the x-axis?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. For a line to be parallel to the x-axis, its slope must be zero. 2. The slope of the line between the two points is given by the formula: slope = (y2 - y1)/(x2 - x1). Substitute the given points: slope = ( (4k - 5) - (2k + 1) )/(8 - 3). 3. Simplify the numerator: (4k - 5) - (2k + 1) = 4k - 5 - 2k - 1 = 2k - 6. 4. Simplify the slope: slope = (2k - 6)/5. 5. Set the slope equal to zero: (2k - 6)/5 = 0  => 2k - 6 = 0. 6. Solve for k: 2k = 6, so k = 3.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>3</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The sentence 'The newly renovated hotel lobby has a beautiful stained glass ceiling.' is irrelevant.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>In a single‐elimination tournament with 512 (2^9) teams having a strict ranking of strength (so that the stronger team always wins), the teams are randomly seeded into the bracket. After all 511 matches have been played, Joy is given the match results. She must now produce a list of teams with the guarantee that this list contains the third-best team. What is the minimum possible length of such a list?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Observe that the tournament has 9 rounds (since 2^9 = 512). The champion wins 9 matches, beating 9 opponents. Among these, one of them, who reached the final, is the runner-up (i.e. the second-best team). The remaining 9 - 1 = 8 teams defeated by the champion are potential candidates for the third-best team (if the third-best met the champion before the final).\n2. Meanwhile, the runner-up has won in 8 matches (all rounds before the final, because the final is lost to the champion). The 8 teams that lost to the runner-up (all in its half of the bracket) are also potential candidates for the third-best team (if the third-best was in the other half and lost to the runner-up).\n3. Since the champion’s 9 opponents include the runner-up, we consider the set of candidates as: (champion's opponents excluding the runner-up) with 8 teams and (runner-up's opponents) with 8 teams. These two sets lie in different halves of the bracket and are disjoint.\n4. Therefore, by creating a list containing these 8 + 8 = 16 teams, Joy is guaranteed to include the third-best team, because in any possible tournament draw the third-best team must have lost to either the champion or the runner-up.\n5. It can be shown that no smaller collection of teams would always contain the third-best team regardless of how the bracket is arranged.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>16</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The sentences 'The new policy change has been implemented in only a handful of countries so far.' and 'Rainbow Dash issue starts off somewhere on the plane, but not on a circle.' along with the extraneous number '463' in the final sentence are not needed.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>For each positive integer n, there is a circle centered at the origin with radius n. A point (Rainbow Dash) starts at some point in the plane that is not on any of these circles and travels in a fixed direction along a straight line. Along her path she first crosses a circle after traveling (√5)/5 units, then crosses a second circle after traveling an additional √5 units, and then crosses a third circle after traveling another (3√5)/5 units. What is the total distance she travels from her starting point until she crosses the third circle?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Identify the distances traveled between successive circle crossings. They are d1 = (√5)/5, d2 = √5, and d3 = (3√5)/5.\nStep 2: The total distance traveled is the sum d1 + d2 + d3.\nStep 3: Write all terms with a common denominator: d1 = √5/5, d2 = 5√5/5, d3 = 3√5/5.\nStep 4: Sum the distances: (√5/5 + 5√5/5 + 3√5/5) = (1√5 + 5√5 + 3√5)/5 = (9√5)/5.\nStep 5: Therefore, the total distance traveled is (9√5)/5 units.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>9√5/5</answer>"
}

