  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Given a 4-dimensional unit hypercube, a bug starts at the vertex (0,0,0,0). In how many ways can the bug reach the vertex (1,1,1,1) by taking exactly 4 steps along the edges of the hypercube?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Each step along an edge of the hypercube changes one coordinate (from 0 to 1 or vice versa). To go from (0,0,0,0) to (1,1,1,1), each coordinate must be flipped exactly once. The number of ways to order these 4 coordinate changes is given by the number of permutations of 4 items, which is 4! = 24.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>24</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The sentence 'The new restaurant downtown has an excellent happy hour menu.' and the number '947' are irrelevant to solving the problem.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Given a set A with 10 elements, find the number of consistent 2-configurations of A (of order 2 with exactly 2 cells).</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Recognize that a '2-configuration of order 2 with exactly 2 cells' means partitioning the set A into exactly 2 nonempty subsets. \nStep 2: The number of ways to partition a set of n elements into 2 nonempty subsets is given by the Stirling numbers of the second kind S(n,2), which can be computed by the formula S(n,2) = (2^n - 2) / 2 = 2^(n-1) - 1. \nStep 3: Here, n = 10, so S(10,2) = 2^(10-1) - 1 = 2^9 - 1 = 512 - 1 = 511.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>511</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The new coffee shop downtown has an amazing selection of artisanal teas.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>If Matilda paints half of her 947‑unit section red and Ellie paints one third of her 947‑unit section red, what fraction of the entire wall (which is made up of Matilda’s section and Ellie’s section) is painted red?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Assume the wall consists of two equal sections: one for Matilda and one for Ellie. Each section is 947 units. Therefore, the total wall area is 947 + 947 = 1894 units.\\n2. Matilda paints half of her section red, which is (1/2)*947 = 947/2 units.\\n3. Ellie paints one third of her section red, which is (1/3)*947 = 947/3 units.\\n4. The total red area is 947/2 + 947/3. To add these, find a common denominator: \\n   947/2 = (3×947)/6 and 947/3 = (2×947)/6, so the sum is (3×947 + 2×947)/6 = (5×947)/6.\\n5. The fraction of the entire wall painted red is (total red area)/(total wall area) = (947×5/6) / 1894.\\n6. Notice 1894 = 2×947, so the fraction becomes (947×5/6)/(2×947) = 5/(6×2) = 5/12.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>5/12</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The phrase \"income tax return\" in the description of the ray and the sentence \"My favorite type of music is indie folk, have you listened to Fleet Foxes?\" are irrelevant to the problem.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let ABC be an equilateral triangle. From vertex A a ray is drawn into the interior of the triangle so that it reaches one of its sides. When the ray reaches a side it bounces off following the law of reflection – that is, if it arrives with a directed angle α, it leaves with a directed angle 180° − α. After n bounces the ray returns to A without ever landing on the other two vertices. Find all possible values of n.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. One standard way to analyze billiard trajectories in a polygon is to use the unfolding (or reflection) method. In this method, each reflection is replaced by reflecting the entire triangle in its side, so that the ray travels along a straight line in an infinite tessellation of the plane by copies of the triangle. The endpoint of the straight-line path corresponds to a copy of A (the starting vertex) in the unfolded plane.\n2. However, not every image of A in the unfolded tiling represents a return to A in the original triangle. The reflections flip the orientation of the triangle. Only those images reached after an even number of reflections (so that the vertex type agrees with the original vertex A) are acceptable. In many such billiards problems these symmetry/ parity conditions force the periodic orbits starting from a vertex (and not hitting the other vertices) to have an odd number of bounces.\n3. A known result for billiards in an equilateral triangle is that any trajectory starting at a vertex and returning there without hitting another vertex must have an odd number of reflections (i.e. n must be odd). The simplest nontrivial orbit occurs with n = 3 bounces. More generally, using the unfolding method one deduces that a necessary and sufficient condition for a vertex–to–vertex (A to A) trajectory avoiding the other vertices is that n = 2k + 1 for some integer k ≥ 1.\n4. Therefore the only possible values of n are all odd integers greater than or equal to 3.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>All odd integers n ≥ 3</answer>"
}

