  "solution_steps": "1. Note that a, b, c, d, e are positive integers, so each is at least 1 and hence the sum S = a + b + c + d + e is at least 5. Also, we are given S ≤ 10, so S can only be one of the integers 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10.\n2. The product P = a · b · c · d · e is at least 1, since all terms are ≥ 1. The inequality requires that 463 · P ≤ S.\n3. If P = 1 (the minimum, which happens only when a = b = c = d = e = 1), then the inequality becomes 463 ≤ S. But even in this minimal case, S = 5, which does not satisfy 463 ≤ 5.\n4. For any other sequence, P will be greater than 1, making 463 · P even larger. Since S is at most 10, there is no possible sequence that satisfies 463 · P ≤ S.\n5. Thus, no sequences can meet the inequality.",
