  "solution_steps": "Step 1: The hypercube W is defined by the 8 inequalities xᵢ ≥ 0 and xᵢ ≤ 1, for i = 1,…,4. \nStep 2: The hyperplane H is given by an equation with normal vector parallel to (1,1,1,1) (since it is parallel to x₁+x₂+x₃+x₄=0). Thus H has the form x₁+x₂+x₃+x₄ = c, where c is chosen so that the intersection is nondegenerate (a true 3-dimensional slice). \nStep 3: The intersection W ∩ H is the set of all points in H that also satisfy 0 ≤ xᵢ ≤ 1. In the induced description inside the hyperplane H, each of the inequalities coming from the hypercube may contribute a bounding facet (face) of the resulting 3-dimensional polyhedron if the corresponding hyperplane (e.g., xᵢ=0 or xᵢ=1) actually cuts through H. \nStep 4: There are 8 such inequalities (4 for xᵢ ≥ 0 and 4 for xᵢ ≤ 1) for i = 1,…,4. For an appropriate choice of c (for example, any c in the interval (1,3) ensures that every one of the 8 hypercube facets is intersected by H), each inequality yields a 2-dimensional face of the intersection polyhedron. \nStep 5: Hence, the maximum number of faces (facets) of the intersection polyhedron is 8.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>8</answer>"
}

{
