  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>If an L shape (formed by three congruent squares) is right subdivided into four smaller L shapes – and this subdivision process is repeated successively – then after 2005 subdivisions (so that there are 4^(2005) L shapes in all), how many of these L shapes are in the same orientation as the original one?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: The key is to notice that the subdivision rule is such that each L shape produces four smaller L shapes in one subdivision. A careful analysis (or a drawing of the actual dissection) shows that exactly one of the four new L shapes has the same orientation as the original L shape.\nStep 2: Since every L (regardless of its orientation) subdivides in the same way, each L shape “contributes” exactly 1 L in the original orientation at the next stage.\nStep 3: At stage 0 (before any subdivision) there is 1 L shape (the original) in the desired orientation. At the first subdivision there will be 1 L, out of the 4 produced from the original, that has the same orientation.\nStep 4: In subsequent subdivisions every L shape (even those not in the desired orientation) will produce exactly one L shape of the original orientation. Thus the number of L shapes in the original orientation does not multiply by 4 but by 1 for each L shape from the previous stage.\nStep 5: Therefore, if we denote by f(n) the number of L shapes in the original orientation after n subdivisions, then f(0)=1 and f(n)=1×f(n−1)=1 for each L shape, but note that the total number of L shapes overall is 4^n. Because each original L “sponsors” one L in the desired orientation (per full set of 4 produced by it), the relation is f(n)=4^(n−1) for n≥1.\nStep 6: For n = 2005, the number of L shapes with the same (original) orientation is 4^(2005−1)=4^(2004).",
  "final_answer": "<answer>4^2004</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>\"The new coffee shop on Main Street has an excellent selection of pastries.\" and the extraneous \"463\" in \"like both lentils 463 and chickpeas\" are not relevant to the problem.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>In a survey of 100 students, 68 like lentils, 53 like chickpeas, and 6 like neither. How many students like both lentils and chickpeas?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Let L be the set of students who like lentils and C be the set of students who like chickpeas. We have |L| = 68 and |C| = 53. 2. Since 6 students like neither, the number of students who like at least one of the two is 100 - 6 = 94. 3. Using the principle of inclusion-exclusion, we write: |L ∪ C| = |L| + |C| - |L ∩ C|. Substituting the known values: 94 = 68 + 53 - |L ∩ C|. 4. Solve for |L ∩ C|: |L ∩ C| = 68 + 53 - 94 = 121 - 94 = 27.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>27</answer>"
}

