  "final_answer": "<answer>53</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"I've always wondered what the best way to cook a perfect soufflé is, have you tried using a water bath?\", \"cells 463 if the door between them is unlocked\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>There is a grid of height 2 stretching infinitely in one direction. Between any two edge‐adjacent cells of the grid there is a door that is locked with probability 1/2 independently of all other doors. Philip starts in a corner of the grid (in the starred cell). Compute the expected number of cells that Philip can reach, assuming he can only travel between cells if the door between them is unlocked.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Interpret the grid as a 2×∞ ladder (2 rows and infinitely many columns in one direction) with cells connected by horizontal and vertical edges. The starting cell is in a corner (say, the top cell of column 0).\n2. In column 0, aside from the guaranteed starting cell, the cell in the other row becomes reachable if the vertical door is unlocked (with probability 1/2). Thus, the number of cells in column 0 is 2 with probability 1/2 and 1 with probability 1/2; the expected number is (1/2)*2 + (1/2)*1 = 1.5.\n3. For moving to column 1, horizontal doors are checked from every cell in column 0. If there is only 1 cell (when the vertical door in column 0 was closed), then the chance to move horizontally from that cell is 1/2. If column 0 has 2 cells (when the vertical door was open), then there are two horizontal doors. Since each door is independently open with probability 1/2, the chance that at least one is open is 1 − (1/2)^2 = 3/4. Overall, the probability to extend from a reached column to the next one is (1/2)*(1/2) + (1/2)*(3/4) = 1/4 + 3/8 = 5/8.\n4. Notice that columns beyond 0 are reached one after the other: column 1 is reached with probability 5/8, column 2 with (5/8)^2, etc. Each reached column, by similar reasoning, has an expected 1.5 cells (since upon entry you get 1 cell and have an independent chance 1/2 of also getting the other cell via the vertical door).\n5. Therefore, the total expected number of cells in the entire reachable cluster is the sum over columns: E(total cells) = 1.5 × [1 + (5/8) + (5/8)^2 + …] = 1.5 / (1 − 5/8) = 1.5 / (3/8) = 1.5 × (8/3) = 4.\n",
  "final_answer": "<answer>4</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"Did you know that the new coffee shop downtown serves an amazing cappuccino?\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Ten gangsters are standing on a flat surface, and the distances between them are all distinct. At twelve o’clock, each of them fatally shoots the one among the other nine gangsters who is the nearest. At least how many gangsters will be killed?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Represent each gangster as a point in the plane. Each gangster selects his unique nearest neighbor to shoot, forming a directed graph with 10 vertices where each vertex has an outdegree of 1. \n2. Notice that the shot result is that a gangster dies if at least one other gangster has him as his nearest neighbor. To minimize the total number of different gangsters shot (i.e. killed), we want as many gangsters as possible to have the same nearest neighbor so that multiple shooters target a single gangster. \n3. One effective idea is a star configuration: Place one gangster (call him the 'central') in the middle and the other nine gangsters around him, arranged so that each peripheral gangster’s closest neighbor is the central gangster. (All distances are made distinct by slightly perturbing positions if needed.) \n4. In this arrangement, the nine peripheral gangsters shoot the central gangster. Now, consider the central gangster: his nearest neighbor cannot be himself, so he must shoot one of the peripheral gangsters. \n5. In summary, the central gangster is shot by nine others and one of the periphery is shot by the central gangster. Therefore, exactly 2 distinct gangsters are killed. \n6. It is not possible to have only one gangster killed because every gangster must shoot someone; the shooter’s target will count as a casualty. Thus, the minimum number of gangsters killed is 2.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>2</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The sentence about the new coffee shop downtown and its latte art is not needed to solve the math problem.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let a₁, a₂, a₃, a₄, a₅ be real numbers whose sum is 20. Determine with proof the smallest possible value of S = Σ₍₁ ≤ i < j ≤ 5₎ ⌊aᵢ + aⱼ⌋.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "We observe that there are 10 pairs (since C(5,2)=10), and for each pair (i,j) one has aᵢ + aⱼ. Note that the sum over all pairs is fixed because\\n  Σ₍₁ ≤ i < j ≤ 5₎ (aᵢ + aⱼ) = (n-1)(a₁ + a₂ + ... + a₅) = 4 · 20 = 80.\\nNow, for each pair we can write aᵢ + aⱼ = ⌊aᵢ + aⱼ⌋ + {aᵢ + aⱼ}, where {x} is the fractional part with 0 ≤ {x} < 1.\\nThus,\\n  Σ ⌊aᵢ + aⱼ⌋ = Σ (aᵢ + aⱼ) - Σ {aᵢ + aⱼ} = 80 - Σ {aᵢ + aⱼ}.\\nSince there are 10 pairs and each fractional part is less than 1, the maximum total of all fractional parts can be made arbitrarily close to (but never equal to) 10. In other words, we can choose the numbers a₁, …, a₅ so that each aᵢ + aⱼ is arbitrarily close to an integer from below. By doing so, the sum of the fractional parts can be made arbitrarily close to 10, making Σ ⌊aᵢ + aⱼ⌋ arbitrarily close to 80 – 10 = 70.\\nA construction that illustrates the optimal behavior is as follows. One may try a symmetric approach by taking four of the numbers equal to some x and the fifth equal to 20 – 4x. Then, the pairwise sums come in two types:\\n • Sums among the four equal numbers: aᵢ + aⱼ = 2x (6 pairs).\\n • Sums between x and (20 – 4x): aᵢ + a₅ = 20 – 3x (4 pairs).\\nWe want to choose x so that both 2x and 20 – 3x are just slightly below some integers. Suppose we pick an even integer p = 2k and arrange x so that 2x is just less than p and simultaneously 20 – 3x is just less than the integer q = 20 – 3k. Then, the floors are:\\n ⌊2x⌋ = p – 1 = 2k – 1 and ⌊20 – 3x⌋ = q – 1 = 20 – 3k – 1.\\nThus the total sum is\\n  S = 6(2k – 1) + 4(20 – 3k – 1) = 12k – 6 + 4(19 – 3k) = 12k – 6 + 76 – 12k = 70.\\nThough the exact values cannot give a fractional part equal to 1 (since they are always strictly less than 1), one can get arbitrarily close. Hence, the minimum possible sum of floors is 70 and this value is best possible when the numbers are chosen suitably (in the limiting sense, one can approach 70, and by an appropriate construction one shows that 70 is indeed the lower bound).",
  "final_answer": "<answer>70</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The new restaurant downtown has an amazing selection of vegan options.; 463; blanched no other balls.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>A bag contains 8 red balls and some white balls, and no other balls. If 5/6 of the balls in the bag are white, how many white balls are in the bag?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Let the total number of balls be T. Since there are only red and white balls and the bag contains 8 red balls, the number of white balls is T - 8. According to the problem, 5/6 of the balls are white, so (5/6)T = T - 8. To solve for T, subtract (5/6)T from T: T - (5/6)T = (1/6)T = 8. Multiplying both sides by 6 gives T = 48. Finally, the number of white balls is T - 8 = 48 - 8 = 40.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>40</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The new coffee shop downtown has a really cozy atmosphere.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>In a math test, there are easy and hard questions. The easy questions are worth 3 points and the hard questions are worth D points. (1) If all the questions are changed to be worth 4 points, the total score of the test increases by 16 points. (2) Instead, if the scores are exchanged so that the easy questions are worth D points and the hard ones 3 points, the new total score is (3/2) times the original total. Also, the number of easy questions is 9 times the number of hard questions. Find the total number of questions in the test.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Let the number of hard questions be H and the number of easy questions be E = 9H. The original total score T is given by: T = 3E + D·H = 3(9H) + D·H = H(27 + D). (1) If all questions are worth 4 points, the new total is 4(E + H) = 4(9H + H) = 4·10H = 40H. Since this increases the total by 16 points, we have: 40H = H(27 + D) + 16, which gives H(40 - 27 - D) = 16, so H(13 - D) = 16. (2) When the scores are exchanged, the easy questions get D points and hard questions get 3 points. The new total is: new_total = D·E + 3H = D·(9H) + 3H = H(9D + 3). This new total is (3/2) times the original total: H(9D + 3) = (3/2) × H(27 + D). Cancel H (assuming H ≠ 0): 9D + 3 = (3/2)(27 + D). Multiply both sides by 2: 18D + 6 = 3(27 + D) = 81 + 3D. Rearranging: 18D - 3D = 81 - 6 → 15D = 75, hence D = 5. Substitute D = 5 into equation (1): H(13 - 5) = H(8) = 16, so H = 2. Then, E = 9H = 18. The total number of questions is E + H = 18 + 2 = 20.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>20</answer>"
}

