  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>For a positive integer n, let τ(n) be the number of positive divisors of n. How many integers 1 ≤ n ≤ 50 are there such that τ(τ(n)) is odd?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Recognize that τ(m) is odd if and only if m is a perfect square (because divisors of a non-square come in pairs, while a square has a middle divisor).\nStep 2: Thus, τ(τ(n)) is odd if and only if τ(n) is a perfect square. For numbers ≤ 50, τ(n) (the number of divisors of n) is a small integer. The only perfect squares in the range of possible values of τ(n) are 1, 4, and 9.\nStep 3: Case τ(n) = 1: The number of divisors is 1 only when n = 1.\nStep 4: Case τ(n) = 4: A number n has exactly 4 divisors if it is of the form p^3 (where p is prime) or of the form p*q (where p and q are distinct primes). Counting all such n between 1 and 50 gives 15 numbers.\nStep 5: Case τ(n) = 9: For τ(n) to equal 9, the number n must be a perfect square with divisors count 9. This happens when n = p^2 * q^2 (with p and q distinct primes) or n = p^8. For n ≤ 50, the only possibility is n = 36 (since 36 = 2^2 * 3^2 gives τ(36) = (2+1)(2+1) = 9).\nStep 6: Add the counts: 1 (from τ(n) = 1) + 15 (from τ(n) = 4) + 1 (from τ(n) = 9) = 17.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>17</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"While Anna always takes 947 the cheapest flight from her current city to some city she hasn't visited yet, Bella always continues her tour with the most expensive flight available.\" , \"The new coffee shop downtown has a lovely atmosphere.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>An airline operates flights between any two capital cities in the European Union. Each flight has a fixed price which is the same in both directions, and the flight prices from any given city are pairwise distinct. Anna and Bella wish to visit each city exactly once, not necessarily starting from the same city. While Anna always takes the cheapest flight from her current city to a city she hasn't visited yet, Bella always continues her tour with the most expensive flight available. Is it true that Bella’s tour will surely cost at least as much as Anna’s tour?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "At every city in the tour, the airline offers a set of flights to not-yet-visited cities. Because the prices of flights departing from any city are pairwise distinct, one can order them from cheapest to most expensive. Anna’s rule is to pick the cheapest available flight, while Bella’s rule is to pick the most expensive one. Although the two travelers may start at different cities (and hence the sets of available flights along their tours differ), note that at every stage the cheapest flight in any available set is at most as high as the most expensive flight in the same set. Hence, in every step of the tour, the cost that Bella incurs is at least as high as the cost that Anna incurs if they were choosing from the same set of available options.\n\nSince both tours are Hamiltonian (each covers all cities exactly once) and have the same number of legs, when one sums up the costs leg by leg, it follows that the total cost of Bella’s tour is at least as high as that of Anna’s tour regardless of the particular flight-price configuration. (The inherent structure of having pairwise distinct prices ensures that the cheapest available option is always less than or equal to the most expensive available option in each departure step.)",
  "final_answer": "<answer>Yes, Bella’s tour will surely cost at least as much as Anna’s tour.</answer>"
}

