  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let n > 1 be a positive integer. Each unit square in an n × n grid is colored either black or white so that: (i) any two black squares are connected by a sequence of edge‐adjacent black squares; (ii) any two white squares are connected by a sequence of edge‐adjacent white squares; (iii) every 2 × 2 subgrid contains at least one square of each color. Determine, with proof, the maximum possible difference between the number of black squares and white squares (in terms of n).</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Denote the number of black squares by B and the number of white squares by W. We have B + W = n^2. We assume without loss of generality that B ≥ W, and our goal is to maximize D = B - W.\n2. The condition that every 2 × 2 block must contain at least one square of each color forces a limit on how dominant one color can be. In any 2 × 2 block all squares cannot be the same color, so there is a local balance that must be maintained throughout the grid.\n3. A careful combinatorial analysis (often based on parity and local counting arguments) shows that one cannot have a difference D larger than n when n is even. When n is odd, since n^2 is odd and B + W is odd, the difference D must also be odd. In the extremal configuration, one can achieve D = n − 1.\n4. Constructions exist for each case. For example, for even n one may design a pattern where nearly every 2 × 2 block is “forced” to have three squares of the majority color and one of the minority color, and one can piece these together to obtain D = n while still ensuring that both the black and white regions are connected. Similarly, for odd n a similar construction yields D = n − 1.\n5. Thus, the maximum possible difference between the number of black squares and white squares is n for even n and n − 1 for odd n.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>For an n × n grid satisfying the conditions, the maximum difference is n when n is even and n − 1 when n is odd.</answer>"
}

