  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Each unit square of a 4×4 grid is colored either red, green, or blue. Over all possible colorings of the grid, what is the maximum possible number of L‐trominos (each formed by three connected unit squares in an L shape) that contain exactly one square of each color?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Note that any L‐tromino covers 3 squares and its bounding box is a 2×2 block. In every 2×2 block (which has 4 cells) colored with 3 colors, by the pigeonhole principle one color must appear twice and the other two appear once. In such a 2×2 block, exactly 2 of the 4 possible L‐tromino subformations (obtained by omitting one of the cells) will have all three distinct colors – namely those obtained by omitting one of the cells that has the repeated color. 2. The entire 4×4 grid has 2×2 sub-blocks with top‐left corners at positions (i, j) for i = 1,2,3 and j = 1,2,3, so there are 9 distinct 2×2 blocks. 3. By choosing a coloring that forces every 2×2 block to have the 2-1-1 distribution, each block can contribute 2 colorful L‐trominos. 4. Thus, the maximum possible number of L‐trominos across the grid is 9 blocks × 2 = 18.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>18</answer>"
}

