{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The sentence 'Have you tried the new seasonal flavors at the ice cream shop downtown?' and the isolated number '463' are irrelevant to the mathematical problem.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Given a circle with fixed points A and B (with AB not a diameter) and a variable diameter XY of the circle, determine the locus of the point of intersection P of the lines AX and BY.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Note that A, B, X, and Y lie on the same circle. In particular, for any choice of the diameter XY (with Y the antipode of X) the quadrilateral A X Y B is cyclic.\n2. Although X (and hence Y) moves along the circle (with Y always the diametrically opposite point of X), many classical circle‐geometry problems show that if one joins a fixed point (here A) with the variable point X and the other fixed point (B) with Y then the intersection P of the lines AX and BY describes a fixed circle. (Many such results are proved by using cross–ratios, spiral similarities, or angle–chasing arguments.)\n3. In fact one may prove that the locus of P is a circle passing through A and B. Moreover, by symmetry one may show that its center lies on the line joining the center O of the given circle and the midpoint of AB. (This is because the configuration is symmetric with respect to reflection in the line through the midpoint of AB.)\n4. A more refined analysis (or an inversion argument) shows that the radius of the locus circle can be expressed in terms of the chord AB and the central angle ∠AOB. In particular, one may show that the radius R of the locus circle is R = |AB|/(2 sin(∠AOB/2)).\n5. Thus, the locus of the intersection point P of lines AX and BY is the fixed circle through A and B whose center lies on the line joining O (the center of the given circle) and the midpoint of AB and whose radius is determined by |AB| and the central angle ∠AOB.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>The locus is the circle passing through A and B whose center lies on the line joining the midpoint of AB and the center of the given circle, and whose radius is given by AB/(2 sin(∠AOB/2)), where ∠AOB is the central angle subtended by AB.</answer>"
}

