  "final_answer": "<answer>2016/2017</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The new restaurant downtown has the most delicious vegan options I've ever tried.\", \"The phrase '463 picks up the last match' and 'at unmatchable' are extraneous or garbled. \"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Alex and Bob have 30 matches. They play a game where each player in turn picks up between 1 and 6 matches. The player who picks up the last match wins. How many matches should Alex pick up on his first turn to guarantee a win?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Identify the winning strategy: In a game where players take between 1 and 6 matches, the losing positions are those where the number of remaining matches is a multiple of 7 (i.e. 7, 14, 21, 28, ...). If a player is forced to face a pile that is a multiple of 7, then the opponent can always respond by taking a number of matches that makes the total picked in both turns equal 7, thereby returning the pile to a multiple of 7.\n2. The game starts with 30 matches. To force Bob into a losing position immediately, Alex should remove a number of matches such that 30 minus that number is a multiple of 7. Let x be the number Alex removes. We need (30 - x) mod 7 = 0. Since 30 mod 7 = 2 (because 7*4 = 28, remainder 2), we solve:\n   30 - x ≡ 0 (mod 7)  ⟹  2 - x ≡ 0 (mod 7)  ⟹  x ≡ 2 (mod 7).\n3. Because x must be between 1 and 6, the only possibility is x = 2.\n4. Thus, if Alex removes 2 matches, 30 - 2 = 28 matches remain. Since 28 is a multiple of 7, Bob is in a losing position if Alex plays optimally afterwards.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>2</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>\"I'm really looking forward to trying out that new Ethiopian restaurant downtown this weekend.\" and the extraneous fragment \"463\" in \"rearranging the letters 463 of the other.\"</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>All sequences consisting of five letters from the set {T, U, R, N, I, P} (with repetitions allowed) are arranged in alphabetical order in a dictionary. Two sequences are called anagrams of each other if one can be obtained by rearranging the letters of the other. How many pairs of anagrams are there that have exactly 100 other sequences between them in the dictionary?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Each sequence is a 5‐letter word using the set {T, U, R, N, I, P}. There are 6^5 = 7776 sequences, and they are arranged in lexicographic (dictionary) order. We identify each sequence with a 5-digit number in base 6 (after choosing an order for the letters, e.g. alphabetical order). The rank of a sequence is its base‑6 number plus 1.\n2. Let a and b be two sequences that are anagrams (i.e. they have the same multiset of letters) and suppose a comes before b in the dictionary. The condition that there are exactly 100 sequences between them means that their dictionary positions differ by 101, i.e. rank(b) – rank(a) = 101. Since rank(w) = (numeric value of w) + 1, this implies that the difference of their numeric values is b – a = 101.\n3. Note that if two sequences are anagrams, they have precisely the same multiset of letters and hence the same sum of digits (when we identify letters with digits). In any base (here base 6) the sum of the digits of a number is congruent modulo (base – 1) to the number itself. Thus, if a and b are anagrams, we have a ≡ b (mod 5).\n4. However, we have b = a + 101. Therefore, a + 101 ≡ a (mod 5), which implies 101 ≡ 0 (mod 5). But 101 mod 5 equals 1, not 0. This is a contradiction.\n5. Because the congruence necessary for two anagrams to differ by exactly 101 in their numeric (and hence dictionary) order is impossible, there are no such pairs.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>0</answer>"
}

{
