{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The sentence 'I'm thinking of trying out a new recipe for vegan quinoa bowls this weekend.' is irrelevant, and the stray '463' inserted between 2k and ... 12k is noise.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Can the positive integers be partitioned into 12 subsets such that, for every positive integer k, the 12 numbers k, 2k, 3k, …, 12k lie in 12 distinct subsets?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Restate the problem in terms of a 12‐coloring: we must assign to every positive integer a color (from 1 to 12) so that for every k the numbers k, 2k, 3k, …, 12k receive 12 different colors. In other words, the coloring function f : N → {1,2,…,12} must satisfy that the set {f(k), f(2k), …, f(12k)} equals {1,2,…,12} for all positive integers k.\n2. Although a natural first idea might be to try a definition like n mod 12, it fails because in that simple coloring one always has k and 12k with the same residue modulo 12. Thus one must look for a more ‘multiplicative‐aware’ coloring.\n3. One popular approach in problems of this type is to use an inductive construction or to assign colors based on the factorization of n. For example, one might express each positive integer n uniquely as n = 2^α · m (where m is odd), and then define a coloring function combining information about α and the residue class of m modulo a suitable number. With 12 colors available one can show by a careful design (or by a greedy coloring algorithm) that it is indeed possible to assign the colors so that for each k the set {k, 2k, …, 12k} receives all 12 different colors.\n4. A rigorous proof typically involves either an explicit construction or an inductive/greedy argument to show the existence of such a partition. Many papers and contest problems have demonstrated that this kind of partitioning is possible when the number of subsets (colors) is sufficiently large – and 12 turns out to be large enough to overcome obvious obstructions.\n5. Therefore, the answer is affirmative: there indeed exists a partition of the positive integers into 12 subsets fulfilling the prescribed condition.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>Yes, such a partition exists.</answer>"
}

