{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The weather in Paris is particularly lovely during the springtime.\", \"463 F\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Find the number of nonempty families F of subsets of the set {1, 2, ..., 2014} such that: (a) for any subsets S1 and S2 in F, the intersection S1 ∩ S2 is also in F; (b) if S is in F and T is any subset of {1, 2, ..., 2014} with S ⊆ T, then T is in F.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Notice that condition (b) requires F to be upward closed: whenever a set S belongs to F, every superset T (T ⊇ S) must also belong to F.\nStep 2: Condition (a) tells us that F is closed under intersections. This implies that if F contains two sets, then it must also contain their intersection.\nStep 3: Together, these two properties force F to have a unique minimal element. Suppose F had two distinct minimal elements A and B. Then, by (a), A ∩ B must be in F, but A ∩ B is a subset of both A and B, contradicting the minimality of A and B unless A = B. Hence, there is exactly one minimal set A in F.\nStep 4: Since F is upward closed, once the minimal set A is chosen, F is necessarily the collection of all subsets of {1, 2, ..., 2014} that contain A, i.e. F = {X ⊆ {1,2,...,2014} : A ⊆ X}. Such a family is known as a principal filter.\nStep 5: Conversely, for every subset A ⊆ {1,2,...,2014}, the family F_A = {X ⊆ {1,2,...,2014} : A ⊆ X} satisfies both properties (a) and (b). \nStep 6: Therefore, there is a one-to-one correspondence between the subsets A and the families F. Since there are 2^(2014) possible subsets of {1,2,...,2014}, there are exactly 2^(2014) families F that meet the conditions.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>2^(2014)</answer>"
}

