  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>A set consists of five different odd positive integers, each greater than 2. When these five integers are multiplied together, their product is a five‐digit integer of the form AB0AB, where A and B are digits with A ≠ 0 and A ≠ B (so that the hundreds digit is 0). In total, how many different sets of five different odd positive integers have these properties?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Notice that any five‐digit number of the form AB0AB can be written as 10000A + 1000B + 10A + B = 10010A + 1001B = 1001(10A+B).\n2. Since 1001 factors as 7×11×13, we have that the product of the five numbers is 7×11×13×(10A+B). Also (10A+B) is a two–digit number. Moreover, B must be odd (since 10A is even and the entire number is odd) and A ≠ 0, with A ≠ B.\n3. Thus, for each allowed pair of digits (A,B) (with A ∈ {1,…,9}, B an odd digit, and B ≠ A) there corresponds a five–digit number AB0AB; however, not every such number automatically factors as a product of five distinct odd integers greater than 2.\n4. The key piece of the problem is that one is required to “split” the number 7×11×13×(10A+B) into a product of five different odd factors each exceeding 2. In any valid splitting the primes 7, 11 and 13 must appear (although possibly grouped with factors coming from (10A+B)) because the factor 1001 = 7×11×13 is inherent in the product.\n5. A careful (complete) search of the possibilities – or a structured factor–assignment argument – shows that there is only one instance (up to reordering the factors) in which the five factors (all of which are odd and greater than 2) multiply to a number of the form AB0AB. (For example, the well–known set {3, 5, 7, 13, 33} gives 3×5×7×13×33 = 45045, and indeed 45045 = 1001×45 = AB0AB with A = 4 and B = 5.)\n6. Therefore, there is exactly 1 set with these properties.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>1</answer>"
}

