  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>For each positive integer n, let s(n) be the sum of the squares of the digits of n. For example, s(15) = 1² + 5² = 26. Determine all integers n ≥ 1 such that s(n) = n.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Write the equation s(n) = n, where s(n) is defined as the sum of the squares of the digits of n. \nStep 2: Observe that for any multi-digit number, the maximum possible value of s(n) is limited by the number of digits. For a number with d digits, the maximum s(n) is d * 9² = 81d, but n is at least 10^(d-1). For d ≥ 2, 10^(d-1) grows much faster than 81d. Thus, only very small numbers can possibly satisfy s(n) = n. \nStep 3: Check single-digit numbers (n = 1 through 9):\n    n = 1: s(1) = 1² = 1, so n = 1 works.\n    For any n from 2 to 9, s(n) = n², which is greater than n. \nStep 4: Since for two-digit and larger numbers n will be too high compared to s(n), the only solution is n = 1.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>1</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"I heard the new coffee shop down the street is having a buy-one-get-one-free promotion on their pumpkin spice lattes this weekend.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Sherry is waiting for a train. Every minute, there is a 75% chance that a train will arrive. However, since she is engrossed in her game of sudoku, even if a train arrives, she has a 75% chance of not noticing it (and hence missing the train). What is the probability that Sherry catches the train in the next five minutes?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: In each minute, the probability that a train arrives is 0.75. However, when a train arrives, the probability that Sherry notices (and catches) it is 0.25 (since she has a 75% chance of not noticing it). Thus, the effective probability per minute of catching the train is 0.75 * 0.25 = 0.1875.\nStep 2: The probability that she does not catch a train in one minute is therefore 1 - 0.1875 = 0.8125.\nStep 3: Assuming each minute is independent, the probability that she misses the train in all 5 minutes is (0.8125)^5.\nStep 4: Calculating (0.8125)^5: Note that 0.8125 = 13/16. Therefore, (13/16)^5 = 371293/1048576 ≈ 0.3540.\nStep 5: Hence, the probability that she catches at least one train in five minutes is 1 - (0.8125)^5 ≈ 1 - 0.3540 = 0.6460 (approximately).",
  "final_answer": "<answer>Approximately 64.6%</answer>"
}

