  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>If the mean (average) of 5 consecutive integers is 9, what is the smallest of these integers?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Let the five consecutive integers be n, n+1, n+2, n+3, and n+4.\\nStep 2: Their sum is n + (n+1) + (n+2) + (n+3) + (n+4) = 5n + 10.\\nStep 3: The mean is (5n + 10)/5 = n + 2.\\nStep 4: Set the mean equal to 9: n + 2 = 9.\\nStep 5: Solve for n: n = 9 - 2 = 7.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>7</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>\"Find 574 take the rank of A.\"; \"Not, asked in the contest : A is diagonalisable since real symetric matrix it is not difficult to find its eigenvalues.\"; \"The new coffee shop downtown has excellent customer service.\"</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let A be an n×n matrix with entries A₍ᵢⱼ₎ = i + j. Find the rank of A.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Notice that each entry of the matrix is given by A₍ᵢⱼ₎ = i + j. This expression can be separated into two parts: one that depends only on i and another that depends only on j. Specifically, A₍ᵢⱼ₎ = i + j = f(i) + g(j), where f(i) = i and g(j) = j.\nStep 2: Write A as the sum of two matrices: one, say B, where each entry B₍ᵢⱼ₎ = i (which is independent of j), and another, say C, where each entry C₍ᵢⱼ₎ = j (which is independent of i).\nStep 3: Observe that matrix B can be written as the column vector u = [1, 2, ..., n]ᵀ multiplied by a row vector of all ones. Thus, B = u · [1, 1, ..., 1], which is a rank-1 matrix. Similarly, matrix C can be written as a column vector of all ones multiplied by the row vector v = [1, 2, ..., n]. So, C = [1, 1, ..., 1]ᵀ · v and is also rank 1.\nStep 4: Since A = B + C, and B and C are both rank-1 matrices, the rank of A is at most 2.\nStep 5: For n ≥ 2, the two matrices B and C are linearly independent. Therefore, rank(A) = 2. However, for the special case when n = 1, the matrix A is 1×1 and its rank is 1.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>If n = 1, the rank of A is 1; for n ≥ 2, the rank of A is 2.</answer>"
}
